From Alternative Data to Investment Alpha: A Textual Analysis Case Study

Witold Kozlowski

January 11, 2022

  • 1. Data Sourcing
  • 2. Feature Selection
  • 3. Textual Analysis
  • 4. Deriving Variables
  • 5. Rank Ordering & Quintile Segmentation
  • 6. Alpha Calculation Against Fama-French Factor Model
  • 7. Concluding Remarks
  • 8. About the Author

This is a case study in verifying whether an alternative data set can generate statistically significant alpha in publicly traded stocks. Specifically, we use the publicly available Consumer Financial Protection Bureau’s (CFPB) Complaints Database. We tie the data to 25 publicly traded US consumer facing financial institutions. We extract features from the data and derive variables using textual analysis of the consumer complaint narratives. The derived variable is cosine similarity of the consumer complaint narratives as they change year on year. The main idea is that if the complaints a company receives change year on year, this means something. In this case, it turns out that companies with the largest change (i.e. changers) in their complaints similarity outperform non-changers. We rank these variables by quintile and run these segments against the Fama-French factor model. While the charts for the different quintile portfolios are suggestive, their alphas are unfortunately not statistically significant. The code for this case study will be made available on Github at witolot/consumer_complaints.

1. Data Sourcing

We use the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau’s (CFPB) Complaints Database. These are complaints made against financial products of particular companies (e.g. credit scoring, credit cards, loans).

# Load R libraries
library(tidyverse)
library(tidyquant)
library(lubridate)
library(stringr)
library(quanteda)
library(quanteda.textstats)

# Load data downloaded from from https://files.consumerfinance.gov/ccdb/complaints.csv.zip
df <- read_csv("data/complaints.csv")

2. Feature Selection

We’re mostly interested in the “Consumer complaint narrative” column, which contains unstructured text. While the database goes back to 2011, these consumer narratives only become available from 2015, giving us 7 years of data (Jan 2015 - Dec 2021) with a total of 841,219 non-empty entries (consumers elect whether to disclose their narrative).

3. Textual Analysis

Since we’re interested in the complaints as they pertain to each company, and not so much in the one-by-one complaint entries, we concatenate / collapse all the individual consumer narratives into in one long string for each company for each year. Notice we now only have 164 rows after concatenation.

# Aggregate complaint text by yearmon
df2 <- df %>%
    filter(`Date received`>=as.Date("2015-01-01")) %>%
    select(`Date received`,Company,`Consumer complaint narrative`,Product,`Sub-product`,Issue,`Sub-issue`,`Complaint ID`) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    mutate(year=year(`Date received`)) %>%
    group_by(Company,year) %>%
    summarize(complaint = str_c(`Consumer complaint narrative`, collapse = ". "))

We use the quanteda package to run the textual analysis:

  • Convert dataframe to corpus format
  • Make tokens out of the words
  • Remove stop words (e.g. “a”, “the”)
  • Stem the words (e.g. so we count “fraudulent” and “fraud” as same since stem would be “fraud”)
  • We’d normally also run the tf-idf (i.e. term frequency - inverse document frequency) to assign heavier weights to rarer occurring words but in this case the cosine similarity calculation we use later runs its own weightings logic
# Convert df to corpus
corp_complaints <- corpus(df2, text_field = "complaint")

# Rename doc names in corpus
docid <- paste(df2$Company,df2$year, sep = " - ")
docnames(corp_complaints) <- docid

# Make tokens
toks_complaints <- tokens(corp_complaints, remove_punct = TRUE)

# Remove stop words
toks_complaints <- tokens_select(toks_complaints, pattern = stopwords("en"), selection = "remove")

# Convert to DFM format
dfmat_complaints <- dfm(toks_complaints)

# Stem words
dfmat_complaints <- dfm_wordstem(dfmat_complaints)

4. Deriving Variables

Here’s the key part. We want to calculate the similarity of each Company-Year’s worth of complaints to one another. E.g. We compare Wells Fargo complaints from 2021 to Wells Fargo complaints from 2020 using a similarity score for each year.

# Calculate cosine similarity
tstat_simil <- textstat_simil(dfmat_complaints, method = "cosine")

# Convert to tibble
tstat_simil_df <- as_tibble(tstat_simil)

# Add descriptive tags
tstat_simil_df <- tstat_simil_df %>%
    mutate(
        year1=as.numeric(str_sub(document1,-4,-1)),
        year2=as.numeric(str_sub(document2,-4,-1)),
        company1=sub(" .*", "", document1),
        company2=sub(" .*", "", document2)
    )

And here’s a visualisation of the similarity score (i.e. derived variable). A score of 1 means that the nature of this year’s versus the previous year’s complaints is identical. The closer to zero, the more different is one Company-Year to another.

# Plot graph
tstat_simil_df %>% 
    filter(year1==(year2-1),company1==company2) %>%
    group_by(year1,year2) %>%
        ggplot(aes(x=year2,y=cosine)) + 
            geom_point(col="blue") + theme_classic() + 
            facet_wrap(~company1) +
            theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 35, hjust=1)) +
            labs(title="Cosine Similarity Over Time",subtitle="Year on Year Change",x="")

#Plot graph
tstat_simil_df %>% 
    filter(year1==(year2-1),company1==company2) %>%
    group_by(year1,year2) %>%
    mutate(
        rank = dense_rank(desc(cosine)),
        quantile = ntile(desc(cosine),5),
        date=make_date(year1+2,1,1)) %>%
        ggplot(aes(x=year2,y=quantile)) + 
            geom_line(col="salmon",size=1) + theme_classic() + 
            facet_wrap(~company1) +
            theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 35, hjust=1)) +
            labs(title="Evolution of Similarity Over Time by Company",subtitle="Migration between quintiles is actually quite dynamic",x="")

5. Rank Ordering & Quintile Segmentation

To prepare the similarity score for testing against the Fama-French (FF) factor model, we need to:

  • Rank companies by their similarity score by year
  • Assign these to quintiles
  • Create portfolio weights for processing later in the Fama-French regression model
# Calculate and assign stocks to quantiles by similarity score
simil_var2 <- tstat_simil_df %>% 
    filter(year1==(year2-1),company1==company2) %>%
    group_by(year1,year2) %>% 
    mutate(
        rank = dense_rank(desc(cosine)),
        quantile = ntile(desc(cosine),5),
        date=make_date(year1+2,1,1)
        ) 

# Convert dataframes to xts for processing in portfolio weights
interim <- simil_var2 %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    select(date,company1,quantile) %>%
    filter(date<=as.Date("2021-12-31"))

# Wrangle for quintile 1
q1 <- interim %>% filter(quantile==1) %>% group_by(date) %>% mutate(quantile = quantile/sum(quantile)) %>% spread(company1,quantile) %>% replace(is.na(.), 0)
q1_xts <- xts(as.data.frame(q1)[,-1], order.by=as.data.frame(q1)[,1])

# Wrangle for quintile 2
q2 <- interim %>% filter(quantile==2) %>% group_by(date) %>% mutate(quantile = quantile/sum(quantile)) %>% spread(company1,quantile) %>% replace(is.na(.), 0)
q2_xts <- xts(as.data.frame(q2)[,-1], order.by=as.data.frame(q2)[,1])

# Wrangle for quintile 3
q3 <- interim %>% filter(quantile==3) %>% group_by(date) %>% mutate(quantile = quantile/sum(quantile)) %>% spread(company1,quantile) %>% replace(is.na(.), 0)
q3_xts <- xts(as.data.frame(q3)[,-1], order.by=as.data.frame(q3)[,1])

# Wrangle for quintile 4
q4 <- interim %>% filter(quantile==4) %>% group_by(date) %>% mutate(quantile = quantile/sum(quantile)) %>% spread(company1,quantile) %>% replace(is.na(.), 0)
q4_xts <- xts(as.data.frame(q4)[,-1], order.by=as.data.frame(q4)[,1])

# Wrangle for quintile 5
q5 <- interim %>% filter(quantile==5) %>% group_by(date) %>% mutate(quantile = quantile/sum(quantile)) %>% spread(company1,quantile) %>% replace(is.na(.), 0)
q5_xts <- xts(as.data.frame(q5)[,-1], order.by=as.data.frame(q5)[,1])

Here’s a visualisation of the weights. Since we have 25 stocks in our universe, a quintile will be 5 stocks. Within each quintile, each stock will take a 20% weighting.

knitr::include_graphics("images/q1_weights.png")

And here we calculate the weights for a Q5-Q1 portfolio.

# Construct 130/30 stock portfolio
q5_q1 <- q1 %>% 
    gather(symbol,weight,-date) %>% 
    filter(weight!=0) %>% 
    mutate(weight=weight*-1*1/3) %>% 
    rbind(q5 %>% gather(symbol,weight,-date) %>% filter(weight!=0) %>% mutate(weight=weight*1.33)) %>%
    group_by(date) %>% 
    spread(symbol,weight) %>% 
    replace(is.na(.), 0)
q5_q1_xts <- xts(as.data.frame(q5_q1)[,-1], order.by=as.data.frame(q5_q1)[,1])

And here’s a visualisation of the Q5-Q1 portfolio weight. TBH, not quite sure what’s the best practice for calculating this differential so we went with a long-short portfolio. Long the stocks from the favoured quintile and short the stocks from the disfavoured quintile. The favoured quintile was then weighted at 130 and the disfavoured at 30 to give a 130/30 allocation. Notice that the long stocks sum to above 1.00 and the short stocks have negative weights and sum to -1/3.

knitr::include_graphics("images/q5_q1_weights.png")

6. Alpha Calculation Against Fama-French Factor Model

The code for this section is available in portfolio2.R and can be largely run as is. We’ll skip it in this document for sake of brevity. Go to Line 62 to adjust which quantile you want the calculation to run. q1_xts for Q1, q5_xts for Q5, q5_q1_xts for Q5-Q1.

Here are the resulting portfolios for each quintile. Inspecting the differences visually, it’s clear to verify that Portfolio Q1 performed worst and Q5 second best. The 130/30 long-short portfolio is best.

knitr::include_graphics("images/portfolio_comp.png")

Unfortunately the alpha term isn’t significant in any model. However, even though not statistically significant, there is a gradation of results in the sense that \(\alpha\)Q1 < \(\alpha\)Q5 < \(\alpha\)Q5-Q1, which is what we’d expect to see when running such an exercise.

7. Concluding Remarks

Overall, this is a good first pass. Some ideas on what to do next to perhaps reach a significant alpha term on the Fama-French model:

  • Increase periodicity. Instead of a fixed Jan - Dec yearly comparison with annual rebalancing, do a 12 month rolling window with quarterly rebalancing.
  • Expand stock universe. Check whether increasing number of ticker-tied company names is viable given the dataset.
  • Survivorship bias. One of the top 25 stocks (Ditech Financial LLC) wasn’t included in the portfolio calculations since it delisted due to bankruptcy and Yahoo removed the price series data. Finding an alternative price history source and adding it into the calculations may improve significance.
  • Alternative derived variables. Construct variations of the similarity score. One idea is to add semantic analysis. One could use the Loughran-McDonald financial dictionary and run cosine similarity over this subset instead of the whole corpus.
